    "Title: Introduction
Path: The Many Parts of Nushell
Content:
The Nushell project consists of multiple different repositories and subprojects.

You can find all of them under 
[link: https://github.com/nushell] our organization on GitHub
.
The main Nushell repository can be found 
[link: https://github.com/nushell/nushell] here
. It is broken into multiple crates that can be used as independent libraries in your own project, if you wish so.
The repository of our 
[link: https://www.nushell.sh] nushell.sh
 page, including this book, can be found 
[link: https://github.com/nushell/nushell.github.io] here
.
Nushell has its own line editor which 
[link: https://github.com/nushell/reedline] has its own repository
[link: https://github.com/nushell/nu_scripts] ``nu_scripts``
 is a place to share scripts and modules with other users until we have some sort of package manager.
[link: https://github.com/nushell/nana] Nana
 is an experimental effort to explore graphical user interface for Nushell.
[link: https://github.com/nushell/awesome-nu] Awesome Nu
 contains a list of tools that work with the Nushell ecosystem: plugins, scripts, editor extension, 3rd party integrations, etc.
[link: https://github.com/nushell/showcase] Nu Showcase
 is a place to share works about Nushell, be it blogs, artwork or something else.
[link: https://github.com/nushell/rfcs] Request for Comment (RFC)
 serves as a place to propose and discuss major design changes. While currently under-utilized, we expect to use it more as we get closer to and beyond 1.0.
"
